english:
  title: A Discourse on Mutual Remonstrance in the Office of Prime Minister
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Since records and books have existed, the words and deeds of ministers have offered much to emulate and much to avoid. Taking the most prominent examples, Heaven hears through the hearing of our people, Heaven sees through the sight of our people. Heaven rewards the virtuous and dreads the wicked through the loves and hates of our people. Thus it reaches from Heaven above to the people below—let all with lands be reverent.

    When Gao Yao counseled Shun, he was ashamed that his lord was not like Yao and Shun; when even one person could not find his place, he felt as though pushing himself into a ravine. When Yi Yin assisted Tang, he sought widely for the worthy and capable, placing them in various offices. When Fu Shuo served High Ancestor, he taught: "When reverence overcomes negligence, there is good fortune; when negligence overcomes reverence, there is ruin. When righteousness overcomes desire, there is harmony; when desire overcomes righteousness, there is calamity." This was the Duke of Qi's warning to King Wu: when ministers monopolize the power to bestow blessings and inflict punishments, and feast on delicacies, they bring harm to their households and calamity to their states; the officers become partial and corrupt, and the people become licentious and reckless.

    When the Viscount of Ji counseled King Wu, he spoke of laboring without ceasing morning and night, of not neglecting small matters, for great virtue can be undermined by them—as one cannot complete a nine-fathom mountain with a final basket of earth. When the Duke of Zhao instructed King Wu, he described one who thrice releases his food from his mouth in a single meal, and thrice grasps his hair while bathing—so did he honor worthy scholars. When the Duke of Zhou assisted King Cheng, he kept his own conduct respectful, served his sovereign with reverence, nurtured the people with benevolence, and ruled them with righteousness.

    When Zichan governed Zheng, he led through virtue, regulated through ritual, was cautious in affairs and earned trust, economized in expenditure and loved his people, employing them in their proper season. When Confucius spoke of governance, he taught: establish vegetable plots of five mu, plant them with mulberry trees; the fields of one hundred mu must not be taken during their seasons; schools must be carefully maintained and the principles of filial piety and fraternity must be repeatedly taught. When Mencius expounded upon kingly governance, he said: clarify righteousness and do not scheme for profit; illuminate the Way and do not calculate success. When Dong Zhongshu spoke of the kingly path, he taught: open the sincere heart, extend the public good, recommend the hidden talented, and promote the loyal and beneficial, so that granaries have no surplus cloth and storehouses no surplus grain.

    When Zhuge Liang served as advisor to a ruler, he exhausted his mind and strength in all that he knew, and made it his responsibility to advance worthy persons. When Fang Xuanling assisted Tang's Emperor Taizong, he relied upon loyalty and trustworthiness, and brought peace to righteousness and destiny. When Guo Ziyi preserved his position to the end, he rectified himself to rectify the ruler, knew men and managed affairs. When Zhen Dexiu spoke of the role of prime minister, he taught: correct your own person to correct the ruler's mind, know people and handle affairs.

    Yet there are those who brought ruin: When Shiyun confused the Zhou, he loved riches and monopolized profit, stationing inspectors of slander so that people could only communicate by glances along the road. When Rong Yigong misled the Zhou, he concealed deception to fish for fame, currying favor with the times to win the ruler's affection. When Gongsun Hong drew ridicule, his learning was shallow and his understanding dark; he privately schemed with his kinsmen. When Huo Guang's line was extinguished, it was because he built halls with double walls and accumulated the most fertile fields. When Liang Ji met destruction, it was because he was ornamental without substance, and his desires knew no bound.

    When Zhang Hua and Pei Hui came to calamity, their outward manner was gentle and respectful, yet inwardly they were cruel, partial, and jealous, harming all who displeased them. When Li Yifu betrayed the Tang, he skillfully discerned the ruler's intentions and carefully cultivated his desires, blocking the path of remonstrance and suppressing those superior to himself—his mouth held honey, his belly held swords. When Li Linfu confused the Tang, he was devious and cunning; anyone who did not attach themselves to him he sought to destroy. When Lu Chi misled the Tang, he played with power and mocked wisdom, blocking the people's words and conducting affairs through bribery, accumulating wealth without restraint—eight hundred measures of pepper and other goods in proportion.

    When Yuan Zai met destruction, it was because he envied the worthy and despised the capable, standing alone without peer. When Lu Duosen was banished, it was because he pursued wealth and implemented new laws, drawing in petty men. When Wang Anshi brought calamity to Song, he closed the paths of remonstrance and sought profit through power, accepting bribes and wielding reward and punishment at will. When Jia Sidao brought both household and nation to ruin, he exercised arbitrary authority and lived in endless extravagance.

    Those who enter this office should see what is worthy of emulation and must wish to possess it in themselves; seeing what is worthy of avoidance, they must wish never to possess it in themselves. With caution and reverence, becoming more careful each day, one need not fear falling short of becoming a gentleman, and both household and nation will prosper together. To reverse this is to court inevitable calamity. Alas, how can one fail to be afraid? How can one fail to be reverent?
